<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS: MARKET WATCH; 
</P>
<P>
FRENCH GAME PLAN TO GET FARMERS BOGGLES THE MIND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN SLOAN, ALLAN SLOAN is a financial columnist for Newsday in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the surface, the question of whether regulators in California and eight 
other states should let something called Faraxa Corp. take over Farmers Group's 
insurance operations is about as exciting as watching paint dry. Just the 
application that Faraxa submitted to the Illinois Insurance Department to take 
over Farmers' subsidiary there weighs 15 pounds, according to my bathroom 
scale. The arguments in California's hearings between Faraxa and Farmers 
lawyers are so nit-picky that they sound like doctrinal disputes between 
members of a religious cult. 
</P>
<P>
Why should you care about any of this? Because there is actually something 
interesting going on here. It may even be important. 
</P>
<P>
The fate of Faraxa's bid for Farmers will probably determine whether Sir James 
Goldsmith, the Anglo-French takeover artist, ever gets to make his $21-billion 
hostile bid for BAT Industries, Britain's biggest conglomerate. That would be 
the world's second-largest takeover, after RJR Nabisco. 
</P>
<P>
BAT, which bought Farmers last year, is trying desperately to keep Goldsmith at 
bay, not least because his plans call for selling most of the company and 
firing most of its managers. 
</P>
<P>
If Farmers manages to foil Faraxa, Goldsmith's raid on BAT is probably 
finished. If Faraxa wins, the fun begins. 
</P>
<P>
Faraxa, the would-be buyer of Farmers, is one of about 6 zillion subsidiaries 
of Axa-Midi Assurances, a French insurance company that also has industrial and 
real estate holdings. Axa-Midi has made a deal to buy Farmers from Goldsmith if 
Goldsmith takes over BAT. 
</P>
<P>
What Axa-Midi is trying to pull off is breathtaking. The company wants to use 
$4.5 billion, all of it borrowed money, to buy Farmers. In one stroke, 
Axa-Midi, which doubled its size in 1988 when Axa took over Midi, would 
redouble in size and transform itself from a European company to a worldwide 
giant. 
</P>
<P>
"I can no longer just be a poor little Froggie with my beret on my head," 
Claude Bebear (pronounced BAY-BAY-r), Axa-Midi's chairman, says with a Gallic 
shrug. Given that Europe is turning into a single market, "if we remain only a 
small French insurance company, we will have to fight to survive," he says. 
</P>
<P>
The $4.5 billion for Farmers, plus another $1 billion that Axa-Midi plans to 
use to buy into Hoylake Investments, the company that Goldsmith is using to 
raid BAT, is a good part of the cash portion of Goldsmith's proposed offer. 
Goldsmith can't make the offer, under British rules, until and unless Axa-Midi 
gets regulators' permission to take over Farmers. 
</P>
<P>
If Axa-Midi were an American company, its request to buy Farmers would be 
laughed out of the place. Why? Because its corporate structure is 
incomprehensible to mortal man. And because you can't get away with borrowing 
100% of the purchase price for a takeover in these post-junk, post-Drexel 
Burnham Lambert days, when debt is declasse. 
</P>
<P>
Bebear's plan, which sounds almost reasonable when he explains it, goes like 
this: 
</P>
<P>
The $1 billion to buy into Hoylake comes from cash on hand, or relatively minor 
borrowings by various Axa-Midi companies. To raise the $4.5 billion to buy 
Farmers, Axa-Midi will borrow $2.25 billion from banks and the other $2.25 
billion from Goldsmith by giving him promissory notes rather than cash. 
(Goldsmith will turn the notes into cash to help pay for his BAT offer by 
selling the notes or borrowing against them.) 
</P>
<P>
Axa-Midi will repay the bank loans, plus interest, with dividends from Farmers. 
It will repay the $2.25 billion of notes to Goldsmith, which have relatively 
short maturities, from profits, from selling shares in group companies to 
investors or by disposing of non-insurance assets, such as an African beer 
company that it just unloaded for several hundred million dollars, or by 
selling some of its enormously valuable landholdings in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
"We can easily raise this money," Bebear says. "The $2.25 billion of notes 
isn't really debt. It's deferred equity." 
</P>
<P>
"He can call it deferred equity or whatever he wants, but it's still short-term 
debt," says Charles Schultz, Farmers' senior vice president for finance. 
Schultz, who has been sparring with Bebear for months, seems to have come to 
like the man. "With his charm and our facts, it would be a slam-dunk," Schultz 
says. 
</P>
<P>
Does Bebear's plan make sense? Can he really raise the money he says he can? 
Can Farmers pay Axa-Midi enough dividends to repay the bank debt without 
putting its policyholders at risk? 
</P>
<P>
Beats me. It's hard enough to analyze a U.S. insurance company because 
insurance is complicated to begin with and firms keep entirely different sets 
of books for stockholders and for insurance regulators. A French insurance 
company, especially this one, is a mind-blower. 
</P>
<P>
Axa-Midi has so many twists and turns that its structure looks like someone's 
small intestine, not a corporation. 
</P>
<P>
I'll spare you most of the details. All you have to know is that the company 
ultimately is based on three large mutual insurance companies, which are owned 
by their policyholders. Piled atop them is a group of controlled, partly owned 
subsidiaries that own pieces of each other. The piece de resistance is 
Compagnie du Midi, acquired in 1988 when its managers ran to Bebear asking for 
protection against a raid by an Italian company, Generali-Assicurazioni 
Generali. Axa now controls Midi by owning 60% of an Axa-Generali holding 
company that owns a majority of Midi's stock. 
</P>
<P>
See? Isn't that clear? And that's the simple version. 
</P>
<P>
The point of all this is to introduce Axa-Midi and Claude Bebear, who are 
clearly going to be heard from again. And to give you an idea of how the world 
has changed to the point where European companies we never heard of can make 
10-digit takeover bids for American firms. It's a sobering thought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Axa-Midi's Claude Bebear: "The $2.25 billion of notes isn't really debt. 
It's deferred equity." SCOTT ROBINSON / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
