<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: SCIENCE / MEDICINE; 
</P>
<P>
KANGAROO GETS PACEMAKER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Surgeons have implanted a heart pacemaker into an ailing kangaroo at the San 
Francisco Zoo. 
</P>
<P>
Middle-aged, 80-pound Skippy is believed to be the first zoo animal to receive 
a pacemaker, zoo officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The surgery was performed last week by three heart surgeons and four 
anesthesiologists. 
</P>
<P>
A zoo spokeswoman said Wednesday that Skippy, 7 years old, was in guarded 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
Mike Sulak, the zoo's curator of mammals, said the kangaroo had a heartbeat of 
only 18 to 40 beats per minute before surgery, far slower than the normal 125 
to 150 range. 
</P>
</TEXT>
