<P>
W.VA. TEACHERS IGNORE GOV.'S CALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHARLESTON, W.Va. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hundreds of striking teachers ignored Gov. Gaston Caperton's request to return 
to the classroom today and called for direct talks with the governor. 
</P>
<P>
The strike over pay began last Wednesday and by today had spread to 46 of the 
state's 55 counties. 
</P>
<P>
Classes were canceled in at least 27 counties for more than 150,000 pupils, 
about half the state's enrollment. 
</P>
<P>
A proposed settlement of the state's first teacher walkout collapsed over the 
weekend. The largest teachers union says West Virginia has the second-lowest 
teachers' salaries in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 16,000-member West Virginia Education Assn. recommended 
continuing the strike until Caperton promises to call a special legislative 
session to consider pay raises. But the governor said he won't consider calling 
a special session until the teachers go back to work. 
</P>
<P>
Last week, Atty. Gen. Roger Tompkins declared the strike illegal and said any 
teachers who walk off the job can be suspended, fired, barred from teaching for 
a year and charged with misdemeanors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
